@node Introduction "Introduction"

@{b}Introduction to GFonts@{ub}

GEN and GHelvetica replaces the XEN and XHelvetica if you are using
a 1:2 resolution. It improves the appearance of the system and MUI
on a 640x256 or 640x200 screen. They are both based on the fonts they
are to replace, so Martin Huttenloher should also have some credit.

All fonts are pixeled with @{"Typeface" link Typeface} by David Kinder.
@endnode


@node Typeface "Typeface"

@{b}Typeface@{ub}

Typeface is an editor for bitmap fonts. In addition, outline fonts can
be loaded with specific dimensions, altered if required, and saved out as
bitmap fonts. Having an outline font also saved as a bitmap font means
that if an application requests the font in a size stored as a bitmap,
then the bitmap version is used, otherwise the outline font is converted
to the correct size, which generally takes time and memory.

© 1995-96 David Kinder

Aminet:text/misc/Typeface.lha

@endnode


@node Installation "Installation"

@{b}Installation@{ub}

Copy the contents of the Fonts directory into FONTS: or any directory
which is assigned to it.
@endnode


@node Usage "Usage"

@{b}Usage of GFonts@{ub}

Wherever fonts are set, change as follows:
  @{b}Default MWB or MUI@{ub}        @{b}Change to@{ub}
   XEN/8 or XEN/9            GEN/6
   XHelvetica/9              GHelvetica/7
   XHelvetica/11             GHelvetica/8
   XHelvetica/13             GHelvetica/9

N.B. The fonts MUI uses is set at quite a lot of places in its prefs.
Each gadget that uses a font can have it set as prefered.

@endnode


